"# Chapter 10: Polyrhythm

*When two rhythms live in the same time, but count it differently.*

---

## The same beat, two ways of dividing it

In Chapter 5 you learned rhythm as meter — beats grouped into measures, time signatures telling you how many beats per bar, and everything marching in step. A quarter-note pulse is a quarter-note pulse; an eighth is half that; everyone subdivides the beat the same way.

But what happens when **two voices subdivide the beat differently at the same time?**

You get **polyrhythm** — the layering of two (or more) independent rhythmic streams that share a common pulse but divide it into different groupings. The classic example: **three notes in the time of two** (a triplet against duplets), or **two notes in the time of three**. The result is a cross-rhythm — a pattern that pulls against itself, creating rhythmic tension and momentum.

Polyrhythm is foundational in many musical traditions — West African drumming, Afro-Caribbean dance music (calypso, soca, salsa), Latin jazz, funk, and twentieth-century concert music. It's also a **programming problem**: you need to schedule events at times that don't fall on the same subdivision grid.

This chapter teaches you to **layer rhythms that don't evenly divide each other**, to hear the cross-patterns they create, and to build grooves that lock into place when played together — even though, individually, each part seems to push against the beat.

We'll start with the simplest polyrhythm (**3-against-2**, three evenly-spaced events in the time of two beats), then build a **calypso-style groove** that layers a syncopated bassline, a clave pattern, and a percussive chord stab — each voice counting time its own way, all locking into the same bar.

---

## 3-against-2: the fundamental cross-rhythm

The simplest polyrhythm is **3-against-2**: three evenly-spaced notes played in the span of two beats, against a steady two-note pulse.

Here's what that looks like in code. We'll use `(beat ...)` to schedule drum hits, and calculate the timing by hand:

```scheme
(define (three-against-two)
  (transport/tempo 90)
  
  ;; The \"2\" part: two quarter notes
  (beat \"kick\" 0)
  (beat \"kick\" 1)
  
  ;; The \"3\" part: three evenly-spaced hits in 2 beats
  ;; Each hit is 2/3 of a beat apart
  (beat \"rim\" 0)
  (beat \"rim\" (/ 2 3))
  (beat \"rim\" (/ 4 3)))

(three-against-two)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; schedules six drum hits at calculated beat offsets; tempo 90 BPM; kick on beats 0 and 1 (duple), rim at 0, 2/3, 4/3 (triple); produces a 2-beat polyrhythm -->

[VISUAL: A two-beat staff showing the kick pattern (two quarter notes on beats 0 and 1) in the lower voice, and the rim pattern (three evenly-spaced notes across the same two beats) in the upper voice. Note-sprites for the kick and rim hits, sized 16×16, bopping at their respective rates. The triplet notes visibly don't align with the duple grid — the second rim hit lands between the two kicks, the third lands after the second kick. Annotation: \"3 in the time of 2\".]

Run that. You hear the kick drum marking the two-beat pulse, and the rim shot cutting across it in three even parts. The second rim hit falls **between** the two kicks — it doesn't land on a beat. That's the cross-rhythm.

The feel is unsettled — it pulls. Your ear wants to resolve the pattern. When you loop it (repeat the same two bars), the pattern locks and starts to groove. The tension becomes momentum.

Let's loop it:

```scheme
(define (three-against-two-loop)
  (transport/tempo 90)
  
  (define (pattern-bar start-beat)
    ;; Duple: kicks on beat 0 and 1
    (beat \"kick\" start-beat)
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 1))
    
    ;; Triple: rims at 0, 2/3, 4/3
    (beat \"rim\" start-beat)
    (beat \"rim\" (+ start-beat (/ 2 3)))
    (beat \"rim\" (+ start-beat (/ 4 3))))
  
  ;; Loop it four times
  (pattern-bar 0)
  (pattern-bar 2)
  (pattern-bar 4)
  (pattern-bar 6))

(three-against-two-loop)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; calls pattern-bar four times at beat offsets 0, 2, 4, 6; each bar schedules the same 3-against-2 pattern; total duration 8 beats; produces a looping polyrhythm -->

Now the pattern repeats. After two or three cycles, your ear locks onto both rhythms at once — the steady duple kick **and** the rolling triple rim. They form a composite groove.

---

## The math of polyrhythm: finding common time

Polyrhythm works because **both patterns share a common cycle length**. In 3-against-2, the cycle is **2 beats** (or equivalently, **3 triplet-eighths**, or **6 sixteenth-notes** — pick your subdivision). The duple pattern divides those 2 beats into 2 parts; the triple pattern divides the same 2 beats into 3 parts.

To schedule events at those times, you calculate:
- **Duple spacing:** 2 beats ÷ 2 events = 1 beat per event.
- **Triple spacing:** 2 beats ÷ 3 events = 2/3 beat per event.

Then you place each event at `start-beat + (spacing × index)`.

Here's a helper that schedules *n* evenly-spaced hits over *dur* beats:

```scheme
(define (polyrhythm-layer sound n dur start-beat)
  ;; Schedule n evenly-spaced hits of 'sound' over 'dur' beats,
  ;; starting at start-beat.
  (let ((spacing (/ dur n)))
    (letrec ((loop (lambda (i)
                     (when (< i n)
                       (beat sound (+ start-beat (* i spacing)))
                       (loop (+ i 1))))))
      (loop 0))))

(define (demo-polyrhythm-layer)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  
  ;; 4-against-3 in 4 beats
  (polyrhythm-layer \"kick\" 3 4 0)  ;; 3 kicks over 4 beats
  (polyrhythm-layer \"snare\" 4 4 0)) ;; 4 snares over the same 4 beats

(demo-polyrhythm-layer)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; defines polyrhythm-layer helper (recursive loop scheduling n evenly-spaced beats over dur); demo schedules 4-against-3 pattern (3 kicks + 4 snares over 4 beats); produces a 4-beat polyrhythm -->

[VISUAL: A four-beat staff showing two voices: the kick pattern (three evenly-spaced hits across 4 beats: at 0, 4/3, 8/3) and the snare pattern (four evenly-spaced hits: at 0, 1, 2, 3). Note-sprites for both, 16×16, showing the offset alignment. Annotation: \"4-against-3\".]

Run that. You get a 4-against-3 pattern — four snare hits (one per beat) against three kick hits (spaced every 4/3 beats). The kicks don't line up with the snare grid except at the downbeat.

This is the **general pattern for polyrhythm**: pick your cycle length (in beats), pick two numbers that don't share a common factor (or do, for a more consonant feel — 4-against-2 is really just a 2:1 ratio, which is simpler), and divide the cycle evenly by each number.

---

## Clave: the rhythmic anchor

Many polyrhythmic traditions use a repeating **rhythmic ostinato** as an anchor — a short, asymmetric pattern that loops and defines the groove. In Afro-Caribbean music, this is called **clave** (from the Spanish word for \"key\").

The most famous clave is the **son clave**, a five-note pattern over two bars (eight beats). It comes in two forms: **3-2 clave** (three hits in the first bar, two in the second) and **2-3 clave** (two hits first, three second). Here's the 3-2 version:

```scheme
(define (son-clave-3-2 start-beat)
  ;; Son clave (3-2): hits at beats 0, 1.5, 3, 5, 6.5
  ;; (relative to start-beat)
  (beat \"clave\" start-beat)
  (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 1.5))
  (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 3))
  (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 5))
  (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 6.5)))

(define (demo-clave)
  (transport/tempo 110)
  
  ;; Loop the clave twice
  (son-clave-3-2 0)
  (son-clave-3-2 8))

(demo-clave)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; defines son-clave-3-2 (five clave hits at beat offsets 0, 1.5, 3, 5, 6.5); demo loops it twice (at beat 0 and beat 8); tempo 110 BPM; produces 16 beats of clave -->

[VISUAL: A two-bar (eight-beat) staff showing the son clave pattern: hits at 0, 1.5, 3 (first bar — the \"3\" side), 5, 6.5 (second bar — the \"2\" side). Note-sprites for the clave hits, 16×16, each bopping at eighth-note tempo (the clave sound is short and sharp). Annotation: \"Son clave (3-2)\".]

The pattern is **asymmetric** — it doesn't divide the eight beats evenly. That asymmetry is what gives it momentum. It pushes forward.

Clave is not itself a polyrhythm — it's a single rhythmic line — but it **creates the framework for polyrhythm**. Other instruments play patterns that lock to the clave or push against it, creating cross-rhythms within the two-bar cycle.

---

## Building a calypso groove

Calypso and soca music (from Trinidad and Tobago) are built on polyrhythmic layering: a syncopated bassline, a percussive chord stab (often on the offbeat), and a clave-like rhythmic anchor, all interlocking over a steady kick-and-snare pulse.

We'll build a simple calypso groove in four layers:

1. **Kick and snare** — the steady pulse (four-on-the-floor kick, snare on 2 and 4).
2. **Clave** — the rhythmic anchor (son clave, 3-2 form).
3. **Bass** — a syncopated bass line that anticipates beat 1 (hits on the \"and\" of beat 4).
4. **Chord stab** — a short, accented chord on the offbeat (the \"and\" of beat 2).

Each layer has its own rhythmic feel; together they lock into a groove.

Here's the full program:

```scheme
(define (calypso-groove)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  
  ;; Layer 1: Kick and snare (steady pulse, two bars = 8 beats)
  (define (drums start-beat)
    ;; Kicks on every beat
    (beat \"kick\" start-beat)
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 1))
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 2))
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 3))
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 4))
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 5))
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 6))
    (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat 7))
    
    ;; Snares on 2 and 4 (and 6, which is \"2\" of the second bar)
    (beat \"snare\" (+ start-beat 2))
    (beat \"snare\" (+ start-beat 4))
    (beat \"snare\" (+ start-beat 6)))
  
  ;; Layer 2: Son clave (3-2)
  (define (clave start-beat)
    (beat \"clave\" start-beat)
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 1.5))
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 3))
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 5))
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 6.5)))
  
  ;; Layer 3: Bass (syncopated — anticipates beat 1)
  (define (bass start-beat)
    ;; Bass hits on beat 0, the \"and\" of 2 (2.5), and the \"and\" of 4 (4.5)
    ;; in the first bar; then on beat 5 and the \"and\" of 6 (6.5) in the second
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.8)
    (note/place-at start-beat)
    
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.7)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2.5))
    
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.8)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 4.5))
    
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.8)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 5))
    
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.7)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 6.5)))
  
  ;; Layer 4: Chord stab (offbeat accent)
  (define (chord-stab start-beat)
    ;; Short chord on the \"and\" of beat 2 (2.5) and beat 6 (6.5)
    ;; We'll use three notes to form a simple triad (A major: A C# E)
    (note/strike 'A3 'sixteenth 0.9)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2.5))
    (note/strike 'C#4 'sixteenth 0.9)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2.5))
    (note/strike 'E4 'sixteenth 0.9)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2.5))
    
    (note/strike 'A3 'sixteenth 0.9)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 6.5))
    (note/strike 'C#4 'sixteenth 0.9)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 6.5))
    (note/strike 'E4 'sixteenth 0.9)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 6.5)))
  
  ;; Compose the layers (two-bar cycle, loop it twice)
  (drums 0)
  (clave 0)
  (bass 0)
  (chord-stab 0)
  
  (drums 8)
  (clave 8)
  (bass 8)
  (chord-stab 8))

(calypso-groove)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; tempo 120 BPM; defines four layers (drums: kick on every beat + snare on 2/4/6; clave: son 3-2 at 0/1.5/3/5/6.5; bass: syncopated A2 eighths at 0/2.5/4.5/5/6.5; chord-stab: A-major triad sixteenths at 2.5 and 6.5); composes all four layers over two 8-beat cycles (total 16 beats); produces a calypso groove -->

[VISUAL: A two-bar (eight-beat) score showing all four layers stacked vertically: kick (bottom staff, quarter notes on every beat), snare (hits on beats 2, 4, 6), clave (middle staff, five hits as per son 3-2), bass (bass clef, syncopated eighths at 0, 2.5, 4.5, 5, 6.5), and chord stab (treble clef, triad sixteenths at 2.5 and 6.5). Note-sprites for each voice, 16×16, color-coded by layer. The offbeat bass and chord hits visibly land between the kick grid. Annotation: \"Four layers, one groove\".]

Run that. You hear:
- The steady kick pulse (every beat).
- The snare accent on 2, 4, and 6 (the backbeat).
- The clave cutting across the pulse.
- The bass anticipating beat 1 and pushing the groove forward with its offbeat hits.
- The chord stab punching on the \"and\" of 2 and 6, adding a syncopated accent.

Each layer has its own rhythmic identity, but together they lock. The bass and chord stab are **syncopated** — they land on offbeats (the \"and\" of the beat, which is halfway between two quarter notes, or 0.5 beats after the downbeat). The clave is **asymmetric** — its pattern doesn't repeat within a single bar. The kick and snare are **steady** — they mark the pulse.

This is polyrhythm in action: **multiple independent rhythmic streams, each counting time differently, all sharing the same cycle**.

---

## Syncopation as rhythmic tension

Syncopation is a special case of polyrhythm: **accenting a weak beat or an offbeat**, creating a temporary shift in where the listener expects the emphasis to land. In the calypso groove above, the bass hits on the \"and\" of beat 4 (4.5) — that's an offbeat. Your ear expects the accent on beat 1 (the downbeat), but the bass arrives early, creating **anticipation**.

Anticipation is a fundamental tool in dance music. It propels the rhythm forward — the groove doesn't wait for the downbeat; it pushes into it.

You can create syncopation by **scheduling a note slightly before or after the beat** where the listener expects it. Here's a simple syncopated pattern:

```scheme
(define (syncopated-pattern)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  
  ;; Expected: notes on beats 0, 1, 2, 3 (square, on the beat)
  ;; Actual: notes on 0, 1.5, 2, 3.5 (syncopated — the \"and\" of 1 and 3)
  (beat \"rim\" 0)
  (beat \"rim\" 1.5)
  (beat \"rim\" 2)
  (beat \"rim\" 3.5))

(syncopated-pattern)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; tempo 100 BPM; schedules four rim hits at 0, 1.5, 2, 3.5; the second and fourth hits land on offbeats; produces a syncopated 4-beat pattern -->

The second and fourth hits land **between** the beats. That's syncopation. It makes the pattern feel like it's leaning forward.

---

## Cross-rhythm: when the downbeat moves

A more complex form of polyrhythm is **cross-rhythm** — when one voice implies a different meter than the underlying pulse, making it sound like the downbeat has shifted.

A classic example: **hemiola**, a 3-against-2 pattern where three half-notes are played in the span of two bars of 3/4 time, making it feel like the meter has shifted to 2/4 for those bars.

Here's a simpler version: a pattern that plays three evenly-spaced accents over four beats, making it sound like the music is in 3/4 even though it's in 4/4:

```scheme
(define (cross-rhythm-demo)
  (transport/tempo 90)
  
  ;; Underlying 4/4 pulse: kick on every beat
  (beat \"kick\" 0)
  (beat \"kick\" 1)
  (beat \"kick\" 2)
  (beat \"kick\" 3)
  
  ;; Cross-rhythm: accented snare every 4/3 beats (3 hits over 4 beats)
  (beat \"snare\" 0)
  (beat \"snare\" (/ 4 3))
  (beat \"snare\" (/ 8 3)))

(cross-rhythm-demo)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; tempo 90 BPM; kick on beats 0-3 (4/4 pulse); snare at 0, 4/3, 8/3 (three evenly-spaced hits over 4 beats); produces a 4-beat cross-rhythm -->

[VISUAL: A four-beat staff in 4/4 time showing the kick on every quarter note (beats 0, 1, 2, 3) and the snare hits at 0, 4/3 (~1.33), and 8/3 (~2.67). The snare pattern doesn't align with the 4/4 grid except at beat 0. Note-sprites for kick and snare, 16×16. Annotation: \"The snare implies 3/4, the kick states 4/4\".]

Run that. The kick says \"this is 4/4.\" The snare says \"no, this is 3/4.\" Both are true at the same time. That's cross-rhythm.

---

## Polyrhythm as a programming problem

Polyrhythm forces you to think about **time as data** — not just \"play this note,\" but \"play this note at **this exact fractional beat position**.\" You can't rely on a fixed grid (like \"every quarter note\"); you need to calculate the timing.

The tools you have:
- **Arithmetic**: `(/ 4 3)` is a beat position (4/3 beats = 1.333... beats).
- **Loops and recursion**: to schedule a repeating pattern without writing every event by hand.
- **Helpers like `polyrhythm-layer`**: to abstract the pattern (n events over dur beats) so you can reuse it.

This is the same approach you'll use for more complex rhythmic ideas — tuplets (5 notes in the time of 4), metric modulation (changing the tempo mid-phrase), and rhythmic phasing (two identical patterns starting at different times and drifting apart). Polyrhythm is the foundation.

---

## The finale: a layered calypso ostinato

Let's build a richer version of the calypso groove — a full eight-bar phrase with four layers, each entering one by one (a technique called **additive rhythm**), building up to a dense polyrhythmic texture.

We'll use:
1. **Kick and snare** (steady pulse).
2. **Clave** (son 3-2, looped).
3. **Bass** (a two-bar syncopated pattern, looped four times).
4. **Chord stabs** (offbeat accents, sparse at first, denser later).

Here's the program:

```scheme
(define (layered-calypso-finale)
  (transport/tempo 126)
  
  ;; Helper: son clave (3-2) over one 8-beat cycle
  (define (clave start-beat)
    (beat \"clave\" start-beat)
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 1.5))
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 3))
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 5))
    (beat \"clave\" (+ start-beat 6.5)))
  
  ;; Helper: kick and snare over one 8-beat cycle
  (define (drums start-beat)
    ;; Kick on every beat
    (let loop ((b 0))
      (when (< b 8)
        (beat \"kick\" (+ start-beat b))
        (loop (+ b 1))))
    ;; Snare on 2, 4, 6
    (beat \"snare\" (+ start-beat 2))
    (beat \"snare\" (+ start-beat 4))
    (beat \"snare\" (+ start-beat 6)))
  
  ;; Helper: syncopated bass over one 8-beat cycle
  (define (bass start-beat)
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.8)
    (note/place-at start-beat)
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.7)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 2.5))
    (note/strike 'C3 'eighth 0.8)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 4.5))
    (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.8)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 5))
    (note/strike 'G2 'eighth 0.7)
    (note/place-at (+ start-beat 6.5)))
  
  ;; Helper: chord stab (A major triad, offbeat)
  (define (stab beat-pos)
    (note/strike 'A3 'sixteenth 0.95)
    (note/place-at beat-pos)
    (note/strike 'C#4 'sixteenth 0.95)
    (note/place-at beat-pos)
    (note/strike 'E4 'sixteenth 0.95)
    (note/place-at beat-pos))
  
  ;; === Build the phrase ===
  
  ;; Bars 1-2: drums enter
  (drums 0)
  
  ;; Bars 3-4: clave enters
  (drums 8)
  (clave 8)
  
  ;; Bars 5-6: bass enters
  (drums 16)
  (clave 16)
  (bass 16)
  
  ;; Bars 7-8: chord stabs enter (sparse: on 2.5 and 6.5 of each bar)
  (drums 24)
  (clave 24)
  (bass 24)
  (stab 26.5)  ;; \"and\" of beat 2, bar 7
  (stab 30.5)  ;; \"and\" of beat 6, bar 7
  
  ;; Bars 9-10: full texture (add more stabs)
  (drums 32)
  (clave 32)
  (bass 32)
  (stab 34.5)
  (stab 36.5)
  (stab 38.5))

(layered-calypso-finale)
```

<!-- BUILD: complete program; runs standalone; tempo 126 BPM; defines helpers for clave, drums, bass, and chord stab; builds an 8-bar (64-beat) additive phrase: bars 1-2 drums only, bars 3-4 +clave, bars 5-6 +bass, bars 7-10 +chord stabs (increasing density); each layer schedules events at calculated beat positions; produces a layered calypso ostinato -->

[VISUAL: An eight-bar reduction score (treble + bass clef + percussion staff) showing the additive layering: bars 1-2 show only kick and snare; bar 3 adds the clave line; bar 5 adds the bass (syncopated eighths); bar 7 adds sparse chord stabs (one or two per bar); bars 9-10 show the full dense texture with more frequent stabs. Note-sprites scattered across all layers, 16×16, color-coded (kick=red, snare=blue, clave=yellow, bass=green, stab=white). The texture visibly thickens bar by bar. Annotation: \"Additive rhythm — each layer enters in turn\".]

Run that. You hear the groove build: first just the pulse, then the clave, then the bass pushing against it, then the chord stabs punctuating the offbeats. By bar 7, all four layers are interlocking — **polyrhythm as architecture**.

This is the finale artifact of the chapter: a **calypso groove that layers four independent rhythmic streams**, each one counting time its own way, all locked into the same cycle. It's honest polyrhythm — not just a triplet ornament over a steady beat, but **multiple simultaneous meters coexisting**.

---

## What you've learned

- **Polyrhythm** is the simultaneous layering of two or more independent rhythmic streams that divide the same time span differently.
- The simplest polyrhythm is **3-against-2** (three evenly-spaced events in the time of two beats).
- You calculate polyrhythmic timing by dividing the cycle duration by the number of events: `spacing = dur / n`.
- **Clave** is a repeating rhythmic ostinato (like the son clave, 3-2 form) that serves as an anchor for polyrhythmic layering.
- **Syncopation** is a form of rhythmic tension created by accenting weak beats or offbeats (like the \"and\" of a beat).
- **Cross-rhythm** makes one voice imply a different meter than the underlying pulse, creating the illusion that the downbeat has shifted.
- **Additive rhythm** is a compositional technique where layers enter one by one, building up a dense polyrhythmic texture.
- Polyrhythm is a **programming problem**: you schedule events at fractional beat positions using arithmetic and loops.

Polyrhythm teaches you to hear **multiple timelines at once** — to hold two (or more) simultaneous ways of counting in your head, and to let them push and pull against each other to create momentum. It's a foundational skill for groove-based music (calypso, soca, funk, Afro-Cuban jazz) and for twentieth-century concert music (Stravinsky, Bartók, Reich).

In the next chapter, we'll explore **world percussion** — layered drum patterns from African, Japanese, and Indian traditions, where polyrhythm is the **default texture**, not an ornament.

---

## End-of-chapter questions

1. **Concept recall:** What is the difference between polyrhythm and syncopation?

2. **Calculate it:** If you want to play 5 evenly-spaced notes in the span of 4 beats, what is the spacing (in beats) between each note?

3. **Make it groove:** Write a program that layers a 4-against-3 polyrhythm (4 hi-hat hits and 3 kick hits, over 4 beats), looped four times. Use `(beat ...)` to schedule the hits.

4. **Syncopate it:** Take a simple four-beat pattern (quarter notes on beats 0, 1, 2, 3) and **shift the second and fourth notes** to the offbeat (the \"and\" of beats 1 and 3). Write the program and describe how the feel changes.

5. **Clave + bass:** Write a program that plays the son clave (3-2 form) over two bars, with a bass note (your choice of pitch) on every clave hit. Does it groove, or does it feel busy? Why?

6. **Build your own:** Compose a two-bar polyrhythmic pattern using **three layers** (kick, snare, and one pitched instrument). At least one layer must be syncopated (hits on an offbeat). Make it loop twice (four bars total). Run it and describe what you hear.


---

## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### The simplest polyrhythm: 2-against-3

We'll start with the classic **hemiola** — two beats in the time of three, or three in the time of two.

```scheme
;; Two against three: the basic hemiola
;; One voice divides a measure into two halves,
;; the other divides the same measure into three thirds.

(define (two-against-three)
  (let ((measure-beats 6))  ;; 6 eighth-notes = one measure, cleanly divisible by 2 and 3
    ;; Voice 1: two pulses (on beats 0 and 3)
    (at-beat 0 (sfx 'wood-block))
    (at-beat 3 (sfx 'wood-block))
    
    ;; Voice 2: three pulses (on beats 0, 2, 4)
    (at-beat 0 (sfx 'clave))
    (at-beat 2 (sfx 'clave))
    (at-beat 4 (sfx 'clave))))

(two-against-three)
```

`[VISUAL: Two parallel timelines over 6 beats. Top line: wood-block strikes at 0 and 3. Bottom line: clave strikes at 0, 2, 4. Vertical gridlines every beat. The composite pattern shows the interlock.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire two-against-three; schedule sfx events at the specified beats; verify the composite rhythm is audible -->

You hear six strikes total, but they don't fall on a single pulse — they weave. The wood-block divides time in half; the clave divides it in thirds. Together they create a six-note composite that *neither instrument plays alone*.

---


### The Cuban clave: a foundational rhythmic cell

The **clave** (Spanish: \"key\") is a two-measure rhythmic pattern that underpins much Afro-Cuban music. It's a five-note pattern spread across two measures, asymmetric and driving. The most common form is the **son clave** in 3-2 orientation:

```scheme
;; The son clave (3-2)
;; Measure 1: three strikes (the \"three\" side)
;; Measure 2: two strikes (the \"two\" side)

(define (son-clave-3-2)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Measure 1 (beats 0–4): three strikes
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'clave))
  
  ;; Measure 2 (beats 4–8): two strikes
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 7 (sfx 'clave)))

(son-clave-3-2)
```

`[VISUAL: Staff with two measures in 4/4. Clave strikes marked as x above the staff at the specified beats. The asymmetry is visible: measure 1 dense, measure 2 sparse.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire son-clave-3-2; schedule clave sfx at the given beats; verify the five-strike pattern across two measures -->

The son clave is *not* evenly spaced — its power comes from the irregularity. It creates a tension between the stated meter (4/4) and the felt pulse (syncopated, pulling against the downbeats). Other instruments *lock to the clave* — the pattern becomes the rhythmic foundation of the entire ensemble.

---


### Layering: bass drum on the downbeats

Now add a bass drum playing straight quarter notes — the most regular pulse possible. Against the clave's syncopation, the bass drum grounds the rhythm.

```scheme
;; Clave with bass drum foundation

(define (clave-plus-bass)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Bass drum: straight quarters on every beat
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 4 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 6 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 7 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Clave pattern (son 3-2)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 7 (sfx 'clave)))

(clave-plus-bass)
```

`[VISUAL: Two-staff system. Bottom staff: bass drum on every quarter. Top staff: clave pattern from the previous example. Where they coincide (beats 0, 2, 7), both symbols stack vertically.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire clave-plus-bass; schedule kick and clave sfx; verify the composite groove -->

Now we have a two-layer polyrhythm: the bass drum is *metrically regular* (reinforcing the 4/4 grid), while the clave is *syncopated* (pulling against it). The listener hears both the grid and the disruption of the grid at the same time.

---


### Cross-rhythm: deliberate metric conflict

A **cross-rhythm** is a polyrhythm in which one part implies a *different meter* than the other. A classic example: a 6/8 bass line under a 3/4 melody. Both fit in the same span of time (six eighth-notes), but the *grouping* differs.

```scheme
;; 6/8 bass against 3/4 melody (hemiola in reverse)

(define (six-eight-vs-three-four)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Bass: 6/8 feel (grouped in twos: 1-2, 1-2, 1-2)
  ;; Accents on beats 0, 2, 4
  (at-beat 0 (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.8))  ;; accent
  (at-beat 1 (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.4))
  (at-beat 2 (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.8))  ;; accent
  (at-beat 3 (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.4))
  (at-beat 4 (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.8))  ;; accent
  (at-beat 5 (note/strike 'A2 'quarter 0.4))
  
  ;; Melody: 3/4 feel (grouped in threes: 1-2-3, 1-2-3)
  ;; Accents on beats 0, 3
  (at-beat 0 (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.9))
  (at-beat 1 (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.5))
  (at-beat 2 (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.5))
  (at-beat 3 (note/strike 'E4 'quarter 0.9))
  (at-beat 4 (note/strike 'D4 'quarter 0.5))
  (at-beat 5 (note/strike 'C4 'quarter 0.5)))

(six-eight-vs-three-four)
```

`[VISUAL: Two staves. Bottom staff in 6/8 (beamed in pairs), top staff in 3/4 (beamed in threes), spanning the same six eighth-notes. Accents marked with > symbols. The metric conflict is visible in the beaming.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire six-eight-vs-three-four; schedule notes with velocity accents; verify the two-vs-three grouping is audible -->

The *time signature is a notation convention* — the engine schedules notes at beat positions, not bars. But by varying *velocity* (the accent pattern), we create the *illusion* of two different meters playing simultaneously. The bass *feels* like 6/8, the melody *feels* like 3/4, even though both occupy the same six-beat span.

---


### 5-against-4: a more complex ratio

Not all polyrhythms are simple 2-vs-3. **Five against four** is a staple of West African drumming and modern jazz. To make it work, we need a span of time divisible by both 4 and 5 — the least common multiple is 20.

```scheme
;; Five-against-four over 20 subdivisions

(define (five-against-four)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  ;; Voice 1: four pulses (every 5 subdivisions)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'wood-block))
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'wood-block))
  (at-beat 10 (sfx 'wood-block))
  (at-beat 15 (sfx 'wood-block))
  
  ;; Voice 2: five pulses (every 4 subdivisions)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 4 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 8 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 12 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 16 (sfx 'clave)))

(five-against-four)
```

`[VISUAL: Two timelines over 20 subdivisions. Top: wood-block at 0, 5, 10, 15. Bottom: clave at 0, 4, 8, 12, 16. Vertical gridlines every subdivision. The pattern is dense and interlocking — nine total strikes, only one coincides (beat 0).]`

<!-- BUILD: wire five-against-four; schedule sfx events; verify the composite rhythm -->

Out of nine total strikes, only the first one (beat 0) coincides. The rest weave through each other. The ear hears a flickering, unstable pulse — neither rhythm dominates, and the composite feels like it's constantly *shifting phase*.

---


### The tresillo: a foundational Afro-Caribbean pattern

The **tresillo** (Spanish: \"little triplet\") is a three-note rhythmic cell common in Cuban, Caribbean, and Latin music. It's often notated as **3+3+2** eighth-notes within a measure of 4/4 (total: 8 eighths).

```scheme
;; The tresillo pattern (3+3+2)

(define (tresillo)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Strikes on beat 0, 3, 6 (out of 8 eighth-note subdivisions)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 6 (sfx 'conga-low)))

(tresillo)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure of 4/4, subdivided into eight eighth-notes. Strikes marked at positions 0, 3, 6. Brackets above the staff showing the grouping: [3] [3] [2].]`

<!-- BUILD: wire tresillo; schedule conga-low sfx at 0, 3, 6; verify the asymmetric grouping -->

The tresillo is *asymmetric* — it doesn't divide the measure evenly. That asymmetry gives it a propulsive, off-balance feel. It's the rhythmic backbone of the habanera, the conga, and many salsa patterns.

---


### Layering tresillo with a steady hi-hat

Add a hi-hat playing straight eighth-notes. The tresillo now *stands out against* the steady pulse.

```scheme
;; Tresillo with hi-hat pulse

(define (tresillo-plus-hihat)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Hi-hat: every eighth-note
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 4 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 6 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 7 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  
  ;; Tresillo (3+3+2)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 6 (sfx 'conga-low)))

(tresillo-plus-hihat)
```

`[VISUAL: Two-staff system. Top: hi-hat on every eighth. Bottom: tresillo pattern. Where they coincide (beats 0, 3, 6), symbols stack.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire tresillo-plus-hihat; schedule hihat-closed and conga-low; verify the composite groove -->

Now the listener can hear *both* the grid (hi-hat) and the syncopation (tresillo). The tresillo feels like it's *pushing against* the steady eighths, creating rhythmic tension.

---


### The cascara: the shell of the timbale

The **cascara** is a rhythmic pattern played on the shell (side) of a timbale drum in salsa and mambo. It's a steady, driving pattern that outlines the clave without playing it directly.

```scheme
;; Cascara pattern (one common variant)

(define (cascara)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Measure 1
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  
  ;; Measure 2
  (at-beat 4 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  (at-beat 5.5 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  (at-beat 6 (sfx 'rim-shot))
  (at-beat 7.5 (sfx 'rim-shot)))

(cascara)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the pattern uses half-beat offsets (1.5, 3.5, 5.5, 7.5), which require subdivision finer than the current eighth/sixteenth grid. When GAP-1 closes, this pattern will run as written.

`[VISUAL: Two measures, 4/4. Rim-shot strikes at the specified offsets. The pattern is steady but syncopated — it outlines the clave's pulse without stating it.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 (finer durations) closes, wire cascara; schedule rim-shot sfx at half-beat offsets -->

The cascara is a *commentary* on the clave — it circles around the clave's strikes, reinforcing the groove without doubling it.

---


### The bomba: a Puerto Rican barrel-drum pattern

The **bomba** is a Puerto Rican Afro-Caribbean drumming tradition. The lead drummer improvises, but the accompanying **buleador** (the larger barrel drum) plays a steady pattern that anchors the rhythm.

```scheme
;; Buleador pattern (simplified, one-measure cycle)

(define (buleador)
  (transport/tempo 110)
  ;; Low strikes on 0, 2, high strike on 3
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'conga-high)))

(buleador)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure, 4/4. Low conga strikes at 0 and 2, high conga strike at 3. The pattern is short but propulsive.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire buleador; schedule conga-low and conga-high sfx; verify the three-strike pattern -->

The buleador pattern is *simple* — only three strikes — but it creates a strong downbeat-upbeat alternation (low-low-high) that drives the dance.

---


### Layering bomba with clapping on the offbeats

In live bomba performance, the audience claps on the offbeats. Add handclaps to the buleador pattern:

```scheme
;; Buleador plus offbeat claps

(define (bomba-plus-claps)
  (transport/tempo 110)
  ;; Buleador (low-low-high)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'conga-low))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'conga-high))
  
  ;; Claps on offbeats (1 and 3)
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'clap))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'clap)))

(bomba-plus-claps)
```

`[VISUAL: Two-staff system. Bottom: buleador pattern. Top: claps on beats 1 and 3. The claps fall between the buleador's low strikes, filling the rhythmic gaps.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire bomba-plus-claps; schedule conga-low, conga-high, and clap sfx; verify the layered groove -->

Now we have a two-layer polyrhythm: the drum plays the *ternary* pattern (low-low-high), the claps play the *binary* offbeats. Together they create a four-beat composite that neither part plays alone.

---


### A funk backbeat: snare on 2 and 4

Funk and soul use a strong **backbeat** — the snare drum hits on beats 2 and 4, the *weak* beats of the measure. Against a bass drum on 1 and 3, this creates a classic call-and-response rhythm.

```scheme
;; Funk backbeat: kick on 1 and 3, snare on 2 and 4

(define (funk-backbeat)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  ;; Kick drum on downbeats
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Snare on backbeats
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'snare)))

(funk-backbeat)
```

`[VISUAL: One measure, 4/4. Kick drum at 0 and 2 (downbeats), snare at 1 and 3 (backbeats). The alternation is clear.]`

<!-- BUILD: wire funk-backbeat; schedule kick and snare sfx; verify the backbeat groove -->

This is the *simplest* funk pattern — just four hits — but it defines the genre. The backbeat is *where the listener claps* in a live performance. The kick says \"one,\" the snare says \"two,\" and the cycle repeats.

---


### Adding a hi-hat pattern: the \"and\" of every beat

Now add a hi-hat playing on every eighth-note, alternating between closed and open on the offbeats.

```scheme
;; Funk groove: kick, snare, and hi-hat

(define (funk-groove)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  ;; Kick on 1 and 3
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Snare on 2 and 4
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'snare))
  
  ;; Hi-hat: closed on downbeats, open on upbeats (every eighth)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 0.5 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 2.5 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'hihat-open)))

(funk-groove)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the hi-hat pattern uses half-beat offsets (0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5). When GAP-1 closes, this groove will run as written.

`[VISUAL: Three-staff drum notation. Bottom: kick on 1 and 3. Middle: snare on 2 and 4. Top: hi-hat on every eighth, closed/open alternating.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire funk-groove; schedule kick, snare, hihat-closed, hihat-open sfx -->

Now we have a three-layer polyrhythm: kick (on 1 and 3), snare (on 2 and 4), hi-hat (on every eighth). The composite is a *driving, locked groove* — the foundation of funk, disco, and hip-hop.

