### A calypso bell pattern: the heartbeat of the islands

Calypso and soca music use a **steel pan bell** pattern that outlines the rhythm. This is a two-measure pattern, syncopated and driving.

```scheme
;; Calypso bell pattern (two measures)

(define (calypso-bell)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Measure 1
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 2.5 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'cowbell))
  
  ;; Measure 2
  (at-beat 4 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 6.5 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 7 (sfx 'cowbell)))

(calypso-bell)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the pattern uses half-beat offsets (2.5, 6.5).

`[VISUAL: Two measures, 4/4. Cowbell strikes at the specified beats. The pattern is syncopated — beat 2.5 and 6.5 are offbeats, creating a lilt.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire calypso-bell; schedule cowbell sfx -->

The calypso bell is the *heartbeat* — every other instrument locks to it. It's often played on an actual cowbell or the rim of a steel pan.

