### A soca \"riddim\": layering the driving pattern

Soca (soul + calypso) uses a faster tempo and a more insistent snare pattern. The snare plays *sixteenth-note rolls* leading into the backbeats.

```scheme
;; Soca riddim: fast, driving, with snare rolls

(define (soca-riddim)
  (transport/tempo 140)
  ;; Kick: every beat
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Snare roll into beat 2 (sixteenths at 1.5, 1.75)
  ;; then snare on 2
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 1.75 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'snare))
  
  ;; Snare roll into beat 4
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 3.75 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 4 (sfx 'snare)))

(soca-riddim)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the snare rolls use sixteenth-note offsets (1.5, 1.75, 3.5, 3.75).

`[VISUAL: Drum notation in 4/4 at tempo 140. Kick on every beat. Snare rolls (two sixteenths) leading into beats 2 and 4, with the backbeat snare accented.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire soca-riddim; schedule kick and snare sfx with sixteenth-note rolls -->

The soca riddim is *relentless* — the snare rolls create a sense of acceleration even though the tempo is steady. It's designed to make people move.

