### Triplet feel: swing eighths

So far, all our polyrhythms have used *straight* subdivisions — the beat divides evenly. But much music uses **swing** — the second eighth of each beat is delayed, creating a *triplet feel* (long-short, long-short).

```scheme
;; Swing eighths: simulating triplet feel with delayed upbeats

(define (swing-pattern)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Downbeats (on 0, 1, 2, 3)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  
  ;; Upbeats delayed (at 0.67, 1.67, 2.67, 3.67 — two-thirds of the way through each beat)
  ;; This is a 2:1 triplet ratio
  (at-beat 0.67 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 1.67 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 2.67 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 3.67 (sfx 'hihat-open)))

(swing-pattern)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — true swing requires triplet subdivisions (which GAP-1 will provide). The above uses decimal approximations (0.67 ≈ 2/3 of a beat).

`[VISUAL: One measure, 4/4, with triplet brackets above each beat. Closed hi-hat on beat 1 of each triplet, open hi-hat on beat 3 of each triplet. Beat 2 of each triplet is silent, creating the swing feel.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire swing-pattern with exact triplet subdivisions; schedule hihat-closed and hihat-open sfx -->

Swing is a *micro-polyrhythm* — the upbeats are delayed by a triplet subdivision, creating a constant push-pull against the steady downbeats. Jazz, blues, and much R&B use swing eighths as the default subdivision.

---


### A jazz ride cymbal pattern

The jazz **ride cymbal** pattern is the quintessential swing rhythm: *ding-ding-a-ding, ding-ding-a-ding*. It's a triplet-based pattern with accents on beats 1 and 3.

```scheme
;; Jazz ride cymbal (triplet-based swing pattern)

(define (jazz-ride)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Each beat is divided into triplets: 1-2-3, 1-2-3, 1-2-3, 1-2-3
  ;; Ride plays on 1, 3, and 1 of the next beat (the \"a\")
  
  ;; Beat 0: triplet 1 (accent), triplet 3
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  (at-beat 0.67 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  
  ;; Beat 1: triplet 1
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  (at-beat 1.67 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  
  ;; Beat 2: triplet 1 (accent), triplet 3
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  (at-beat 2.67 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  
  ;; Beat 3: triplet 1
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'ride-cymbal))
  (at-beat 3.67 (sfx 'ride-cymbal)))

(jazz-ride)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — exact triplet subdivisions.

`[VISUAL: Ride cymbal notation in 4/4 with triplet brackets. Strikes on beat 1 and 3 of each triplet group, with accents on beats 0 and 2 (the \"ding\" of \"ding-ding-a-ding\").]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire jazz-ride with exact triplets; schedule ride-cymbal sfx -->

The ride cymbal is the *timekeeping* voice in a jazz trio or quartet. The pianist and bassist *lock to the ride* the way a salsa band locks to the clave.

---


### A shuffle rhythm: hard swing with a backbeat

The **shuffle** is a swing rhythm with a strong backbeat, common in blues and boogie-woogie. The bass plays on every beat (four-on-the-floor), the snare plays on 2 and 4, and the hi-hat swings.

```scheme
;; Shuffle groove

(define (shuffle-groove)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Bass: every beat
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Snare: backbeat (2 and 4)
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'snare))
  
  ;; Hi-hat: swing eighths (delayed upbeats)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 0.67 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 1.67 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 2.67 (sfx 'hihat-open))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'hihat-closed))
  (at-beat 3.67 (sfx 'hihat-open)))

(shuffle-groove)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — triplet subdivisions for exact swing.

`[VISUAL: Three-staff drum notation. Bottom: kick on every beat. Middle: snare on 2 and 4. Top: hi-hat with swing eighths (triplet-based).]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire shuffle-groove; schedule kick, snare, hihat-closed, hihat-open with exact triplet swing -->

The shuffle is *propulsive* — the swing hi-hat against the straight backbeat creates a rolling, driving feel. It's the rhythm of Bo Diddley, Chuck Berry, and early rock and roll.

