### Building a polyrhythm with melodic content: bass riff plus drums

So far, our polyrhythms have been purely *percussive*. Now we add a *pitched* part — a bass riff that plays a syncopated pattern against the drums.

```scheme
;; Funk bass riff with backbeat

(define (funk-bass-and-drums)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  ;; Drums: kick on 1 and 3, snare on 2 and 4
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'snare))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'snare))
  
  ;; Bass riff: syncopated (on 0, 1.5, 2, 3.5)
  (at-beat 0 (note/strike 'E2 'eighth 0.9))
  (at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 'G2 'eighth 0.7))
  (at-beat 2 (note/strike 'E2 'eighth 0.9))
  (at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 'A2 'eighth 0.7)))

(funk-bass-and-drums)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the bass riff uses half-beat offsets (1.5, 3.5).

`[VISUAL: Two-staff system. Bottom staff (bass clef): E2-G2-E2-A2 pattern at the specified beats. Top staff (drum notation): kick and snare backbeat. The bass and drums interlock — the bass's offbeat notes fall between the drum hits.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire funk-bass-and-drums; schedule kick, snare, and bass notes -->

Now the polyrhythm has *harmonic content* — the bass riff is a melody with its own syncopated rhythm, playing *against* the drums. The listener hears both the drums (which mark the meter) and the bass (which pushes against it).

---


### A montuno: the repeating piano pattern in salsa

The **montuno** is a syncopated piano pattern in salsa and Latin jazz. It's a two-measure repeating figure that outlines the harmony while locking to the clave.

```scheme
;; Montuno pattern (simplified, two measures)

(define (montuno)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Measure 1: alternating chords on offbeats
  (at-beat 0.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 0.5 (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 2.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 2.5 (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.6))
  
  ;; Measure 2: same pattern, different chord
  (at-beat 4.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 4.5 (note/strike 'F4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 5.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 5.5 (note/strike 'A4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 6.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 6.5 (note/strike 'F4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 7.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.6))
  (at-beat 7.5 (note/strike 'A4 'eighth 0.6)))

(montuno)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the montuno plays entirely on offbeats (0.5, 1.5, 2.5, ...).

`[VISUAL: Piano grand staff, two measures in 4/4. Treble clef: two-note chords (C-E, C-G alternating in measure 1; D-F, D-A in measure 2) on every offbeat. Bass clef empty (the bass line would be separate). The syncopation is visible — no notes on downbeats.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire montuno; schedule simultaneous note pairs (chords) on offbeats -->

The montuno is *all syncopation* — it deliberately avoids the downbeats, creating a constant rhythmic tension against the bass and drums (which *do* hit the downbeats).

---


### Layering montuno with bass and clave

Now combine the montuno with a bass line (playing roots on downbeats) and the son clave.

```scheme
;; Full salsa rhythm section: clave, bass, montuno

(define (salsa-section)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Clave (son 3-2)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 5 (sfx 'clave))
  (at-beat 7 (sfx 'clave))
  
  ;; Bass: roots on downbeats
  (at-beat 0 (note/strike 'C2 'quarter 0.8))
  (at-beat 2 (note/strike 'C2 'quarter 0.8))
  (at-beat 4 (note/strike 'D2 'quarter 0.8))
  (at-beat 6 (note/strike 'D2 'quarter 0.8))
  
  ;; Montuno: offbeat chords (measure 1)
  (at-beat 0.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 0.5 (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 1.5 (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 2.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 2.5 (note/strike 'E4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 'C4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 3.5 (note/strike 'G4 'eighth 0.5))
  
  ;; Montuno: measure 2
  (at-beat 4.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 4.5 (note/strike 'F4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 5.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 5.5 (note/strike 'A4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 6.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 6.5 (note/strike 'F4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 7.5 (note/strike 'D4 'eighth 0.5))
  (at-beat 7.5 (note/strike 'A4 'eighth 0.5)))

(salsa-section)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — montuno offbeats.

`[VISUAL: Three-staff system spanning two measures. Top: clave pattern. Middle: piano montuno (offbeat chords). Bottom: bass line (roots on downbeats). The three parts interlock — the bass is on-beat, the montuno is off-beat, the clave is asymmetric.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire salsa-section; schedule clave sfx, bass notes, and montuno chords -->

Now we have a *full polyrhythmic texture*: the clave is the asymmetric pulse, the bass is the harmonic foundation (on the beat), and the montuno is the syncopated filler (off the beat). All three parts are independent but locked together.

