### A Brazilian samba: surdo, agogô, and tamborim

Brazilian **samba** is built on polyrhythm. The **surdo** (a large bass drum) plays the foundational pulse, the **agogô** (a double bell) plays a syncopated pattern, and the **tamborim** (a small frame drum) plays fast, intricate rhythms.

```scheme
;; Simplified samba pattern

(define (samba-pattern)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Surdo: bass pulse (on 1 and 3)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Agogô: high-low bell pattern (syncopated)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'cowbell))      ;; high bell
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'cowbell-low))  ;; low bell
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 2.5 (sfx 'cowbell-low))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'cowbell-low))
  
  ;; Tamborim: fast sixteenth-note pattern (simplified)
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 0.25 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 0.5 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 2.25 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 2.5 (sfx 'tambourine))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'tambourine)))

(samba-pattern)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — the agogô and tamborim patterns use half-beat and quarter-beat offsets.

`[VISUAL: Three-staff drum notation. Bottom: surdo (bass drum) on 1 and 3. Middle: agogô bell pattern (high and low bell alternating, syncopated). Top: tamborim (fast sixteenth-note pattern, sparse but driving).]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire samba-pattern; schedule kick, cowbell/cowbell-low, and tambourine sfx -->

Samba is *dense* — many layers, each with its own subdivision. The surdo is the slowest (half-notes), the agogô is medium (eighth-note syncopations), and the tamborim is the fastest (sixteenths). Together they create a *rolling, propulsive texture*.

---


### Adding melody to samba: a simple reco-reco scrape

The **reco-reco** is a Brazilian scraper (a notched bamboo or metal tube). It adds a *pitched scraping sound* to the samba texture.

```scheme
;; Samba with reco-reco

(define (samba-with-reco)
  (transport/tempo 120)
  ;; Surdo
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Agogô
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'cowbell-low))
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 2.5 (sfx 'cowbell-low))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'cowbell))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'cowbell-low))
  
  ;; Reco-reco: scraped on every quarter
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'guiro))
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'guiro))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'guiro))
  (at-beat 3 (sfx 'guiro)))

(samba-with-reco)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — agogô offbeats.

`[VISUAL: Four-staff system. Bottom three: surdo, agogô, reco-reco. The reco-reco plays steady quarters, the agogô syncopates, the surdo grounds. The three parts interlock.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire samba-with-reco; schedule kick, cowbell/cowbell-low, guiro sfx -->

The reco-reco adds a *textural* layer — it's not melodic (it's a scraping noise), but it has a *pitch contour* (the scrape rises and falls). It fills the rhythmic gaps left by the other instruments.

