### A djembe dunun pattern: three-drum ensemble

West African **djembe** ensembles use three **dunun** (bass drums) playing interlocking patterns. Each drum has a different pitch and rhythm.

```scheme
;; Djembe dunun ensemble (simplified)

(define (djembe-dunun)
  (transport/tempo 100)
  ;; Dundunba (lowest drum): plays on beats 0 and 2
  (at-beat 0 (sfx 'kick))
  (at-beat 2 (sfx 'kick))
  
  ;; Sangban (middle drum): syncopated (on 1 and 3.5)
  (at-beat 1 (sfx 'tom-low))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'tom-low))
  
  ;; Kenkeni (highest drum): fast pattern (on 0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5)
  (at-beat 0.5 (sfx 'tom-high))
  (at-beat 1.5 (sfx 'tom-high))
  (at-beat 2.5 (sfx 'tom-high))
  (at-beat 3.5 (sfx 'tom-high)))

(djembe-dunun)
```

*[needs: GAP-1]* — half-beat offsets for sangban and kenkeni.

`[VISUAL: Three-staff drum notation. Bottom: dundunba (low bass drum) on 0 and 2. Middle: sangban (mid tom) on 1 and 3.5. Top: kenkeni (high tom) on 0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5. The three parts interlock — each drum has a different rhythm, and together they create a continuous pulse.]`

<!-- BUILD: when GAP-1 closes, wire djembe-dunun; schedule kick, tom-low, tom-high sfx -->

The dunun ensemble is a *pitched polyrhythm* — each drum has a different tone, and the three rhythms interlock to create a dense, driving texture. The djembe (the lead drum, not shown here) improvises over this foundation.

