## Notes and Additional Considerations from r2 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r2 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### What polyrhythm is (and what it isn't)

**Polyphony** (Ch9) gave you independent melodic lines — each voice has its own pitches, its own contour, its own direction. They sound together, but each sings its own tune.

**Polyrhythm** gives you independent **metric subdivisions** — each voice has its own way of slicing time. One voice subdivides a measure into three equal parts. Another subdivides the same measure into two. Both are *right*, both are *steady*, and when they sound together, you hear a rhythmic texture richer than either alone.

**A simple duple beat** (two pulses per measure) **and a simple triple beat** (three pulses per measure) **are not polyrhythmic by themselves**. Polyrhythm happens when both subdivisions run **in the same span of time** — when three beats fit in the same duration as two beats, so the attacks fall on different fractional positions of the measure and weave together.

The most famous example is **3-against-2**: three notes in the time of two. Play two quarter-notes in one hand, three eighth-note triplets in the other, and you have a classic polyrhythmic cell.

[VISUAL: A two-staff score, one measure. Top staff: two quarter-notes (simple duple). Bottom staff: a triplet bracket over three eighth-note triplets (simple triple). Both span the same measure. Vertical lines show where attacks align (downbeat and end) and where they do not (the middle attacks are offset). The note-sprites on the triplet staff bop faster than the note-sprites on the duple staff, illustrating the different subdivision rates.]

Polyrhythm is everywhere once you listen for it — in African drumming (where multiple bell patterns and hand-drum cycles layer), in Latin clave (the five-stroke pattern that contradicts the pulse), in calypso and soca (where the bass drum walks in one time and the hi-hat ticks in another), in funk (where the snare backbeat, the hi-hat shuffle, and the kick drum syncopation each subdivide the groove differently). It's the grain of the rhythm, the way interlocking pulses give a beat its **feel**.

We call it **polyrhythm** when the subdivisions are steady and maintain their own independent metric logic. We call it **cross-rhythm** when one line's accents contradict another's downbeats, making you hear the pulse in two places at once. Both are in scope for this chapter.

---


### The simplest polyrhythm: 2-against-3 (the hemiola)

Let's start with the **hemiola** — a 2-against-3 pattern so common it has a Renaissance name.

Set the tempo steady. Play three notes evenly spaced across two beats. Then play two notes evenly spaced across the same two beats. Layer them.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 80)

(define (hemiola-three)
  ;; Three evenly-spaced notes across two beats
  (let ((span 2.0)) ;; two beats total
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 60 0.3 0.6) ;; middle C, short
       (wait (/ span 3)))
     '(0 1 2))))

(define (hemiola-two)
  ;; Two evenly-spaced notes across two beats
  (let ((span 2.0))
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 64 0.3 0.7) ;; E, slightly louder
       (wait (/ span 2)))
     '(0 1))))

;; Play them in sequence, then together
(hemiola-three)
(wait 0.5)
(hemiola-two)
(wait 0.5)
;; Now together
(base/at-beat 0
  (hemiola-three)
  (hemiola-two))
```

[VISUAL: Waveform showing the two patterns first separately (three evenly-spaced attacks, then two evenly-spaced attacks), then together (five attacks total, some aligned, some offset). Below, a staff render: top line three notes with a triplet bracket, bottom line two notes, both spanning two beats.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable hemiola-three / hemiola-two example using base/at-beat to layer them; verify attacks at t=0, 2/3, 4/3 (three-stream) and t=0, 1 (two-stream) align and offset as expected -->

You hear the three-stream as a gentle triplet lilt. You hear the two-stream as a steady duple walk. Together, they interlock — the downbeat aligns, the end aligns, but the middle attacks are offset, and that offset is what makes it *groove*.

---


### 3-against-4: a denser weave

Now layer three beats in the time of four. Each stream subdivides the measure differently, and the attacks fall on different fractions.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 100)

(define (triplet-layer)
  ;; Three notes across four beats
  (let ((span 4.0))
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 55 0.25 0.5) ;; low G
       (wait (/ span 3)))
     '(0 1 2))))

(define (four-layer)
  ;; Four notes across four beats (quarter-note pulse)
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.25 0.6)
     (wait 1.0))
   '(62 64 65 67))) ;; D E F G

(base/at-beat 0
  (triplet-layer)
  (four-layer))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, one measure of 4/4. Top staff: three notes with a triplet bracket (spanning all four beats). Bottom staff: four quarter-notes. Attacks on the bottom staff fall on beats 1, 2, 3, 4. Attacks on the top staff fall on beats 1, 2.333..., 3.666..., creating a woven pattern. The note-sprites on the top staff bop in triplet time; on the bottom, in quarter-note time.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable 3-against-4 example; verify attack timing: top staff at t=0, 4/3, 8/3; bottom staff at t=0,1,2,3 -->

Listen for the points where both streams attack together (the downbeat), and for the stretches where they diverge. That divergence is the **grain** — the micro-timing texture that makes polyrhythm feel alive.

---


### The clave: a rhythmic anchor

The **clave** is a five-stroke rhythmic pattern from Afro-Cuban music. It's not a polyrhythm by itself, but it *contradicts* the pulse — it accents beats that aren't downbeats, making you hear the measure in two different ways at once. When you layer a steady bass pulse underneath, the clave becomes a **cross-rhythm** — the clave's accents and the bass's downbeats are independent metric worlds.

The **son clave** (in 4/4) has strokes on: beat 1, the \"and\" of beat 2, beat 4, beat 1 of the next measure, the \"and\" of beat 2 of the next measure. (That's the 3-2 son clave — three strokes in the first measure, two in the second.)

We'll use `(sfx 'woodblock)` for the clave and a low kick for the bass pulse.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 96)

(define (son-clave-3-2)
  ;; 3-2 son clave: two measures
  ;; Measure 1: beat 1, and-of-2, beat 4
  ;; Measure 2: beat 1, and-of-2
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 1
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-2
  (wait 1.0)                     ;; beat 3 (silent)
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 4
  ;; Measure 2
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 1
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-2
  (wait 2.0))                    ;; beats 3-4 (silent)

(define (bass-pulse-two-bars)
  ;; Steady kick on every beat for two measures
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'kick)
     (wait 1.0))
   '(0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (son-clave-3-2)
  (bass-pulse-two-bars))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff percussion score, two measures of 4/4. Top staff (clave): five woodblock attacks marked with x noteheads on beats 1, 2-and, 4 (measure 1) and 1, 2-and (measure 2). Bottom staff (kick): eight quarter-note kicks, one per beat. The clave's attacks align with some kicks (downbeats) and fall between others (offbeats), creating the cross-rhythmic tension.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable son-clave example using sfx 'woodblock and sfx 'kick; verify clave strokes at t=0, 1.5, 3, 4, 5.5 and kicks at t=0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7 -->

Now the groove has a **hook** — the clave pattern is recognizable, catchy, and it pulls against the steady pulse. This is how polyrhythm creates forward motion: the ear wants to reconcile the two streams, and that tension keeps the rhythm driving.

---


### A calypso groove: bass, rimshot, and cowbell

Calypso (and its faster cousin, soca) is built on layered polyrhythm. The bass drum walks in a steady pattern. The rimshot (or side-stick) ticks on the offbeats. The cowbell or agogô plays a syncopated two-bar phrase that contradicts both. Each layer subdivides time differently, and together they lock into a groove that feels effortless but is rhythmically dense.

Let's build a two-measure calypso cell.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 108)

(define (calypso-bass)
  ;; Bass drum: quarter-note walk, but skip beat 2 of each measure
  ;; Measure 1: 1, (2 silent), 3, 4
  ;; Measure 2: 1, (2 silent), 3, 4
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 1
  (wait 1.0)                ;; beat 2 silent
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 3
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 4
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 1 (m2)
  (wait 1.0)                ;; beat 2 silent
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 3
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0))  ;; beat 4

(define (calypso-rimshot)
  ;; Rimshot on the \"and\" of every beat (eighth-note offbeats)
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (wait 0.5)
     (sfx 'rimshot)
     (wait 0.5))
   '(0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7))) ;; eight beats total (two measures)

(define (calypso-cowbell)
  ;; Cowbell: syncopated two-bar pattern
  ;; beats: 1, and-of-2, 3, and-of-4, and-of-1(m2), 3(m2), 4(m2)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0)   ;; 1
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-2
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0)   ;; 3
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-4
  ;; Measure 2
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-1
  (wait 1.0)                   ;; 2 silent
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0)   ;; 3
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0))  ;; 4

(base/at-beat 0
  (calypso-bass)
  (calypso-rimshot)
  (calypso-cowbell))
```

[VISUAL: Three-staff percussion score, two measures of 4/4. Bottom staff (kick): attacks on beats 1, 3, 4 (both measures), beat 2 silent. Middle staff (rimshot): eighth-note x noteheads on every offbeat (and-of-1, and-of-2, and-of-3, and-of-4, both measures). Top staff (cowbell): syncopated attacks on 1, and-of-2, 3, and-of-4 (m1), and-of-1, 3, 4 (m2). The three layers interlock, creating a dense rhythmic texture with attacks on different fractional beat positions.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable calypso groove with kick/rimshot/cowbell; verify bass skips beat 2, rimshot ticks offbeats, cowbell syncopates -->

Listen to how the three layers fit together. The bass anchors the downbeats (mostly). The rimshot fills every gap with a steady tick. The cowbell dances over both, landing on beats and offbeats in a pattern that repeats every two measures. None of them is hard on its own — the complexity comes from the **layering**.

---


### 5-against-4: quintuplet feel

Now a rarer subdivision: **five notes in the time of four beats**. Quintuplets are less common than triplets, but they create a liquid, rolling feel — like the rhythm is spilling forward.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 90)

(define (quintuplet-layer)
  ;; Five notes across four beats
  (let ((span 4.0))
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 58 0.2 0.5) ;; A#
       (wait (/ span 5)))
     '(0 1 2 3 4))))

(define (four-beat-anchor)
  ;; Four steady quarter-notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (note/strike 70 0.3 0.7) ;; higher A#
     (wait 1.0))
   '(0 1 2 3)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (quintuplet-layer)
  (four-beat-anchor))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, one measure of 4/4. Top staff: five notes with a \"5\" tuplet bracket spanning all four beats (quintuplets). Bottom staff: four quarter-notes. The quintuplet attacks fall on fractional beats (0, 0.8, 1.6, 2.4, 3.2), creating a five-against-four polyrhythmic texture. The quintuplet note-sprites bop at a faster, five-fold rate.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable 5-against-4 example; verify quintuplet attacks at t=0, 0.8, 1.6, 2.4, 3.2 and quarter-note attacks at t=0,1,2,3 -->

Quintuplets *[needs: GAP-1]* — the engine doesn't yet have a built-in quintuplet duration (tuplets(5) is on the GAP-1 list), so we're computing the subdivision manually with `(/ span 5)`. Once GAP-1 closes, you'll write `(duration 'quintuplet)` or `(tuplet 5 'eighth)` and the engine will handle the math.

---


### A funk backbeat: layered syncopation

Funk is built on **syncopation** — accenting the offbeats, especially the \"and\" of beat 2 and the \"and\" of beat 4. When you layer a syncopated snare, a straight kick, and a shuffle hi-hat, you get a groove where every layer subdivides differently.

Let's build a one-measure funk cell with kick, snare, and hi-hat.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 104)

(define (funk-kick)
  ;; Kick on 1, and-of-2, 3
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; 1
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'kick) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-2
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 2.0))  ;; 3, then wait through 4

(define (funk-snare)
  ;; Snare on 2, and-of-3
  (wait 1.0)               ;; 1 silent
  (sfx 'snare) (wait 1.0)  ;; 2
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'snare) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-3
  (wait 1.0))              ;; 4 silent

(define (funk-hihat-shuffle)
  ;; Hi-hat: shuffle eighth-notes (swing feel, not straight)
  ;; Play on 1, and-of-1 (delayed), 2, and-of-2 (delayed), etc.
  ;; Simplified: straight eighths for now *[needs: swing timing]*
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'hihat-closed)
     (wait 0.5))
   '(0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (funk-kick)
  (funk-snare)
  (funk-hihat-shuffle))
```

[VISUAL: Three-staff percussion score, one measure of 4/4. Bottom staff (kick): attacks on 1, and-of-2, 3. Middle staff (snare): attacks on 2, and-of-3. Top staff (hi-hat): eighth-note attacks on every eighth subdivision (straight eighths; swing feel marked as *[needs: swing timing]*). The three layers create a syncopated, funky groove with offbeat accents on the snare and kick.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable funk groove with kick/snare/hihat; verify kick on 1, 2.5, 3; snare on 2, 3.5; hi-hat on every eighth; mark swing timing as needing micro-timing adjustment (not yet in engine) -->

The groove locks when the kick and snare land on offbeats while the hi-hat ticks straight through. The ear hears the hi-hat as the grid and the kick/snare as the **rhythm** — the pattern that dances over the grid.

A true **shuffle** feel (swing eighths) would delay every offbeat hi-hat slightly, creating a triplet-based micro-timing. That's *[needs: swing timing / micro-timing control]* — the engine doesn't yet let you nudge note onsets by fractional subdivisions smaller than the current duration set. Once that's in, you'll write `(swing-factor 0.66)` or similar and the offbeats will lilt.

---


### 7-against-4: a rolling, asymmetric pulse

Let's go dense: **seven notes in the time of four beats**. Septuplets are rare in Western music but common in some African and Balkan traditions. They create a rolling, lopsided feel — like the rhythm is tumbling forward, never quite settling.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 80)

(define (septuplet-layer)
  ;; Seven notes across four beats
  (let ((span 4.0))
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 53 0.15 0.4) ;; low F
       (wait (/ span 7)))
     '(0 1 2 3 4 5 6))))

(define (four-beat-anchor-low)
  ;; Four steady quarter-notes, lower pitch
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (note/strike 65 0.3 0.6) ;; higher F
     (wait 1.0))
   '(0 1 2 3)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (septuplet-layer)
  (four-beat-anchor-low))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, one measure of 4/4. Top staff: seven notes with a \"7\" tuplet bracket spanning all four beats. Bottom staff: four quarter-notes. The septuplet attacks fall on fractional beats (0, 4/7, 8/7, 12/7, 16/7, 20/7, 24/7), weaving a seven-against-four polyrhythmic texture. The septuplet note-sprites bop at a seven-fold rate, visibly faster than the steady quarter-note bops below.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable 7-against-4 example; verify septuplet attacks at t=0, 4/7, 8/7, ..., 24/7 and quarter-note attacks at t=0,1,2,3 -->

Septuplets *[needs: GAP-1]* — same as quintuplets, tuplets(7) isn't in the engine yet, so we compute `(/ span 7)` manually. Once GAP-1 closes, you'll have `(tuplet 7 'eighth)` or similar.

The seven-against-four texture is **dense** and **asymmetric**. Only the first and last attacks align. The middle five attacks are offset, and the ear hears them as a continuous roll. This is the grain of polyrhythm at its most complex — not a simple hemiola, but a tangled weave of independent time streams.

---


### Layering multiple polyrhythms: a percussion ensemble

Now let's combine several polyrhythmic cells into a single ensemble. We'll layer:

1. A **steady bass pulse** (quarter-notes, the anchor).
2. A **triplet hi-hat** (three notes per beat, creating a 3-against-4 feel with the bass).
3. A **clave pattern** (cross-rhythmic, five strokes over two measures).
4. A **shaker** playing straight sixteenths (the finest subdivision, filling every gap).

Each layer is rhythmically independent. Together, they create a dense, polyrhythmic groove.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 100)

(define (ensemble-bass-two-bars)
  ;; Quarter-note kick for two measures
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'kick)
     (wait 1.0))
   '(0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)))

(define (ensemble-triplet-hihat)
  ;; Triplet hi-hat: three notes per beat, two measures = 24 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'hihat-closed)
     (wait (/ 1.0 3))) ;; one beat divided into three
   (make-list 24 #t)))

(define (ensemble-clave)
  ;; 3-2 son clave (as before)
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 0.5)
  (wait 1.0)
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 0.5)
  (wait 2.0))

(define (ensemble-shaker)
  ;; Sixteenth-note shaker for two measures = 32 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'shaker)
     (wait 0.25))
   (make-list 32 #t)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (ensemble-bass-two-bars)
  (ensemble-triplet-hihat)
  (ensemble-clave)
  (ensemble-shaker))
```

[VISUAL: Four-staff percussion score, two measures of 4/4. Bottom staff (kick): eight quarter-notes. Next staff up (hi-hat): 24 eighth-note triplets (three per beat). Next staff (clave): five woodblock attacks in the son clave pattern. Top staff (shaker): 32 sixteenth-notes, a continuous stream. The four layers interlock, creating a dense, polyrhythmic texture with attacks on every fractional subdivision — quarters, triplet eighths, syncopated eighths, and sixteenths all sounding together.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable polyrhythmic ensemble with kick/hihat-triplet/clave/shaker; verify bass on quarters, hihat on triplet eighths, clave on son pattern, shaker on sixteenths -->

Listen to the **density**. The shaker is a continuous stream. The hi-hat ticks in triplet time. The clave hooks the ear with its syncopated pattern. The bass anchors everything on the quarter-note grid. Each layer makes sense on its own, but together they create a groove that is rhythmically **thick** — you can't isolate any one layer, because they all interdepend.

This is the essence of polyrhythm: independent time streams that, when layered, create a texture richer than any single stream.

---


### A two-measure soca groove: bass, rim, cowbell, and shaker

Soca (the faster, modern descendant of calypso) builds on the same polyrhythmic foundation but pushes the tempo and adds more syncopation. Let's build a two-measure soca cell with four layers:

1. **Bass drum**: steady quarters on 1, 3, 4 (each measure).
2. **Rim**: offbeat eighths (on the \"and\" of every beat).
3. **Cowbell**: a syncopated two-bar phrase.
4. **Shaker**: continuous sixteenths.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 130)

(define (soca-bass)
  ;; Bass on 1, 3, 4 (both measures)
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 2.0)   ;; 1, skip 2
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; 3
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; 4
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 2.0)   ;; 1 (m2), skip 2
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0)   ;; 3
  (sfx 'kick) (wait 1.0))  ;; 4

(define (soca-rim)
  ;; Rim on every offbeat (and-of-1, and-of-2, and-of-3, and-of-4, both measures)
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (wait 0.5)
     (sfx 'rimshot)
     (wait 0.5))
   '(0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)))

(define (soca-cowbell)
  ;; Syncopated cowbell: 1, and-of-1, 3, and-of-4 (m1), and-of-2, 4 (m2)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5)   ;; 1
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.5)   ;; and-of-1
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.5)   ;; 3
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-4
  ;; Measure 2
  (wait 1.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-2
  (wait 1.0)                   ;; 3 silent
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0))  ;; 4

(define (soca-shaker)
  ;; Continuous sixteenths for two measures
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'shaker)
     (wait 0.25))
   (make-list 32 #t)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (soca-bass)
  (soca-rim)
  (soca-cowbell)
  (soca-shaker))
```

[VISUAL: Four-staff percussion score, two measures of 4/4 at tempo 130. Bottom staff (kick): attacks on 1, 3, 4 (both measures). Next staff (rim): offbeat eighth-notes (and-of-1, and-of-2, and-of-3, and-of-4, both measures). Next staff (cowbell): syncopated attacks on 1, and-of-1, 3, and-of-4 (m1), and-of-2, 4 (m2). Top staff (shaker): continuous sixteenth-notes. The four layers interlock at a fast tempo, creating a driving soca groove.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable soca groove with kick/rim/cowbell/shaker at tempo 130; verify bass on 1,3,4, rim on offbeats, cowbell syncopated, shaker continuous -->

The faster tempo (130 bpm) and the continuous shaker give this groove a **driving**, almost **frantic** energy. The bass and rim anchor it, but the cowbell syncopation keeps it from feeling mechanical. This is soca: relentless, rhythmically dense, and built to make you move.

---


### Cross-rhythm: shifting the downbeat

A **cross-rhythm** is a polyrhythmic pattern where one layer's accents fall on another layer's offbeats, making you hear the downbeat in two different places. The simplest example is a **3-against-4 cross-rhythm**, where a three-beat pattern repeats across four-beat measures, so the three-beat pattern's \"downbeat\" shifts on every repetition.

Let's build a two-measure example where a three-beat motif repeats four times, cycling through different beat positions in the 4/4 grid.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 96)

(define (three-beat-motif start-beat)
  ;; A three-beat rhythmic motif: note on 1, note on 2, note on 3
  ;; Each note is a short chime
  (base/at-beat start-beat
    (note/strike 72 0.2 0.5) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 1 of motif
    (note/strike 74 0.2 0.5) (wait 1.0)   ;; beat 2 of motif
    (note/strike 76 0.2 0.5)))            ;; beat 3 of motif

(define (cross-rhythm-bass)
  ;; Steady bass on beats 1, 3 of both measures (anchoring 4/4)
  (for-each
   (lambda (beat)
     (base/at-beat beat
       (sfx 'kick)))
   '(0 2 4 6))) ;; beats 1, 3 (m1), 1, 3 (m2)

;; Play the three-beat motif starting on beat 0, 3, 6, 9 (wrapping)
;; That's four repetitions of a three-beat cycle across two 4/4 measures
(three-beat-motif 0)
(three-beat-motif 3)
(three-beat-motif 6)
;; (three-beat-motif 9 would be in measure 3, omitted for two-bar scope)

(cross-rhythm-bass)
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, two measures of 4/4. Top staff: a three-note melodic motif (pitches C5-D5-E5) repeats three times, starting on beats 0, 3, 6 (so the motif's \"downbeat\" shifts relative to the measure). Bottom staff: kick on beats 1, 3 (both measures). The motif's attacks align with the kick on beat 0 and beat 6, but on beat 3 the motif's second note aligns with the kick, creating a cross-rhythmic shift.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable cross-rhythm example with three-beat motif repeating across 4/4 measures and bass anchoring 1,3; verify motif starts at t=0,3,6 and bass hits t=0,2,4,6 -->

The motif is steady — it always plays three notes in a row, one beat apart. But because it starts on beat 0, then beat 3, then beat 6, its **phase** shifts relative to the 4/4 measure. The ear hears the motif's \"downbeat\" moving — first it aligns with the measure's downbeat (beat 0), then it starts on beat 3 (the measure's third beat), then on beat 6 (the second measure's third beat). This is cross-rhythm: the pattern's internal pulse contradicts the meter's pulse.

---


### 4-against-3: the inverse hemiola

We started with 3-against-2 (hemiola). Now let's do **4-against-3** — four notes in the time of three beats. This is the inverse: instead of triplets against a duple grid, we have a quadruple subdivision against a triple grid.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 90)

(define (four-against-three-layer)
  ;; Four notes across three beats
  (let ((span 3.0))
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 60 0.2 0.5) ;; middle C
       (wait (/ span 4)))
     '(0 1 2 3))))

(define (three-beat-anchor)
  ;; Three steady beats (quarter-notes in 3/4, or three beats in any meter)
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (note/strike 67 0.3 0.6) ;; G
     (wait 1.0))
   '(0 1 2)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (four-against-three-layer)
  (three-beat-anchor))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, one measure of 3/4 (or a three-beat span). Top staff: four notes spanning three beats (four-against-three subdivision). Bottom staff: three quarter-notes. The four-note attacks fall on fractional beats (0, 0.75, 1.5, 2.25), weaving against the three-beat grid. The four-note layer's note-sprites bop at a faster rate (four divisions per three beats).]

<!-- BUILD: runnable 4-against-3 example; verify four-layer attacks at t=0, 0.75, 1.5, 2.25 and three-layer attacks at t=0,1,2 -->

The 4-against-3 feel is **looser** than 3-against-2 — the four-note layer feels like it's pulling ahead, subdividing the beat more finely than the three-beat anchor. It's common in jazz and fusion, where the drummer might play quarter-note triplets on the ride cymbal while the bass plays straight quarters, creating a 4-against-3 texture.

---


### A polyrhythmic canon: the same melody in two meters

A **polyrhythmic canon** layers the same melody in two different metric subdivisions — one voice plays it in duple time, another in triple time, so the melody unfolds at different rates and the two voices interlock polyrhythmically.

Let's take a simple four-note melody (C-D-E-C) and play it twice: once with each note lasting one beat (four beats total), and once with each note lasting two-thirds of a beat (triplet feel, so the whole melody fits in 8/3 beats ≈ 2.666... beats).

```scheme
(transport/tempo 84)

(define melody-pitches '(60 62 64 60)) ;; C D E C

(define (melody-duple)
  ;; Each note lasts one beat (four beats total)
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.4 0.6)
     (wait 1.0))
   melody-pitches))

(define (melody-triple)
  ;; Each note lasts 2/3 beat (triplet feel, total = 8/3 beats)
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.3 0.5)
     (wait (/ 2.0 3)))
   melody-pitches))

(base/at-beat 0
  (melody-duple)
  (melody-triple))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, spanning four beats. Top staff: melody C-D-E-C in triplet eighths (each note 2/3 beat, total 8/3 beats). Bottom staff: the same melody in quarter-notes (each note one beat, total four beats). Both voices start on beat 0 (C aligns), but then the triplet voice moves faster, so the second note (D) in the triplet voice sounds before the second note in the duple voice, and the two voices diverge and then re-converge near the end (both land on the final C, but offset slightly). The melody is the same, but the rhythmic grid is different, creating a polyrhythmic canon.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable polyrhythmic canon with melody in duple (quarters) and triple (triplet subdivision); verify both start at t=0, duple proceeds at 1-beat intervals, triple at 2/3-beat intervals -->

The two voices sing the **same tune**, but because one moves in duple time and the other in triple time, they diverge and then re-align in a **phase-shifting** pattern. This is a canon in **rhythm** as much as in pitch.

---


### A six-layer polyrhythmic texture: the full ensemble

Now let's build the densest example yet: **six simultaneous polyrhythmic layers**, each with its own subdivision. This is the chapter's **finale artifact** — a polyrhythmic ensemble that demonstrates every technique we've learned.

The six layers:

1. **Bass drum**: steady quarter-notes on 1, 3 (both measures).
2. **Snare**: backbeat on 2, 4 (both measures).
3. **Hi-hat**: triplet eighths (three per beat, continuous).
4. **Clave**: 3-2 son clave (five strokes, syncopated).
5. **Cowbell**: a custom syncopated two-bar pattern.
6. **Shaker**: continuous sixteenths.

Each layer is independent. Together, they create a groove that is **thick**, **driving**, and **polyrhythmically dense**.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 108)

(define (finale-bass)
  ;; Kick on 1, 3 (both measures)
  (for-each
   (lambda (beat)
     (base/at-beat beat (sfx 'kick)))
   '(0 2 4 6)))

(define (finale-snare)
  ;; Snare on 2, 4 (both measures)
  (for-each
   (lambda (beat)
     (base/at-beat beat (sfx 'snare)))
   '(1 3 5 7)))

(define (finale-hihat)
  ;; Triplet hi-hat: three notes per beat, eight beats = 24 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'hihat-closed)
     (wait (/ 1.0 3)))
   (make-list 24 #t)))

(define (finale-clave)
  ;; 3-2 son clave
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 0.5)
  (wait 1.0)
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)
  (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 1.0)
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'woodblock) (wait 0.5)
  (wait 2.0))

(define (finale-cowbell)
  ;; Custom syncopated cowbell: 1, and-of-2, and-of-3, and-of-1(m2), 3(m2), and-of-4(m2)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.5)   ;; 1, then skip to and-of-2
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0)   ;; and-of-2
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-3
  (wait 1.0)                   ;; 4 silent
  ;; Measure 2
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5) ;; and-of-1
  (wait 1.0)                   ;; 2 silent
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.0)   ;; 3
  (wait 0.5) (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 0.5)) ;; and-of-4

(define (finale-shaker)
  ;; Continuous sixteenths, two measures = 32 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'shaker)
     (wait 0.25))
   (make-list 32 #t)))

;; Layer all six
(base/at-beat 0
  (finale-bass)
  (finale-snare)
  (finale-hihat)
  (finale-clave)
  (finale-cowbell)
  (finale-shaker))
```

[VISUAL: Six-staff percussion score, two measures of 4/4 at tempo 108. From bottom to top: kick (quarters on 1,3), snare (quarters on 2,4), hi-hat (triplet eighths, 24 notes total), clave (five syncopated woodblock attacks), cowbell (custom syncopated pattern, six attacks), shaker (continuous sixteenths, 32 notes). The six layers interlock, creating a dense, polyrhythmic texture with attacks on every possible subdivision — quarters, triplet eighths, syncopated eighths, sixteenths. The note-sprites on each staff bop at their own subdivision rate, creating a visual polyrhythmic cascade.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable six-layer polyrhythmic finale with kick/snare/hihat/clave/cowbell/shaker; verify all layers align correctly (kick on 1,3; snare on 2,4; hihat triplets; clave son pattern; cowbell syncopated; shaker continuous sixteenths) -->

This is the **finale artifact** of the chapter: a calypso groove that layers six independent rhythmic streams into a single, cohesive ensemble. Each layer makes sense on its own. Together, they create a groove that is **thick**, **driving**, and **rhythmically alive** — a polyrhythmic texture that feels effortless but is structurally dense.

---


### Polyrhythm as structure: a two-section piece

Polyrhythm doesn't have to be confined to a single groove. You can **structure an entire piece** around polyrhythmic cells, shifting from one texture to another.

Let's write a two-section piece:

- **Section A**: a sparse 3-against-2 hemiola (just two layers, lots of space).
- **Section B**: a dense 4-against-3 groove with bass, hi-hat, and cowbell (three layers, tighter).

Each section lasts four measures.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 100)

;; Section A: sparse 3-against-2 hemiola
(define (section-a-three)
  ;; Three notes per two beats, four measures = 8 beats = 12 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (note/strike 55 0.3 0.4) ;; low G
     (wait (/ 2.0 3)))
   (make-list 12 #t)))

(define (section-a-two)
  ;; Two notes per two beats, four measures = 8 beats = 4 two-beat pairs = 8 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (note/strike 67 0.4 0.5) ;; higher G
     (wait 1.0))
   (make-list 8 #t)))

(define (section-a)
  (base/at-beat 0
    (section-a-three)
    (section-a-two)))

;; Section B: 4-against-3 with bass, hi-hat, cowbell
(define (section-b-bass)
  ;; Kick on 1, 3 (four measures = 16 beats, kick on every other beat)
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'kick)
     (wait 2.0))
   (make-list 8 #t)))

(define (section-b-hihat)
  ;; Four notes per three beats, repeating
  ;; Four measures of 4/4 = 16 beats; 16 beats = (16/3)*4 = 21.33... notes
  ;; Simplified: four-per-three pattern for 12 beats (three measures), then fill fourth measure
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'hihat-closed)
     (wait (/ 3.0 4)))
   (make-list 20 #t)))

(define (section-b-cowbell)
  ;; Syncopated cowbell: custom pattern across four measures
  ;; beats 1, and-of-2, 4, and-of-2(m2), 3(m3), and-of-4(m4)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.5)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 2.5)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.5)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 2.5)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 1.5)
  (sfx 'cowbell) (wait 2.5))

(define (section-b)
  (base/at-beat 0
    (section-b-bass)
    (section-b-hihat)
    (section-b-cowbell)))

;; Play section A, then section B
(section-a)
(wait 8.0) ;; four measures at tempo 100 = 8 beats
(section-b)
```

[VISUAL: A two-section score. Section A (measures 1–4): two staves, top staff playing three notes per two beats (hemiola), bottom staff playing steady half-notes (one per two beats). Sparse texture, lots of space. Section B (measures 5–8): three staves, bottom staff (kick) on beats 1,3, middle staff (hi-hat) playing 4-against-3 subdivision, top staff (cowbell) syncopated. Dense texture, tight groove. The shift from A to B is visually and aurally distinct — from sparse/open to dense/driving.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable two-section polyrhythmic piece with section A (3-against-2) and section B (4-against-3 + percussion); verify section A lasts 8 beats, section B starts at beat 8 and lasts 16 beats (or adjust durations to taste) -->

The piece has **shape** — it starts sparse and open (the hemiola gives you space to breathe), then thickens and drives forward (the 4-against-3 groove with percussion is relentless). This is polyrhythm as **structure**, not just as texture.

---


### A polyrhythmic phrase: melody and counter-melody in different meters

Let's layer a melody in 4/4 with a counter-melody in 6/8 (or, equivalently, a counter-melody that subdivides the same span into six beats while the melody subdivides it into four). The two melodies interlock polyrhythmically.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 96)

(define melody-4 '(60 62 64 65)) ;; C D E F (one note per beat, four beats)
(define counter-6 '(67 65 64 62 60 58)) ;; G F E D C A# (six notes, triplet feel)

(define (melody-in-4)
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.4 0.6)
     (wait 1.0))
   melody-4))

(define (counter-in-6)
  ;; Six notes in the same span as four beats
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.3 0.5)
     (wait (/ 4.0 6))) ;; four beats divided into six
   counter-6))

(base/at-beat 0
  (melody-in-4)
  (counter-in-6))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, spanning four beats. Top staff: melody C-D-E-F in quarter-notes (one per beat). Bottom staff: counter-melody G-F-E-D-C-A# in six equal divisions (each note 2/3 beat). The two melodies start together (C and G on beat 0) and end together (F and A# near beat 4, slightly offset), but in between they diverge — the six-note line moves faster and creates a 6-against-4 (or 3-against-2) polyrhythmic texture. The note-sprites on the top staff bop in steady quarter-time; on the bottom staff, faster (six-fold subdivision).]

<!-- BUILD: runnable polyrhythmic phrase with melody in 4 and counter-melody in 6; verify melody at t=0,1,2,3 and counter-melody at t=0, 2/3, 4/3, 2, 8/3, 10/3 -->

The two melodies are **independent** — each has its own pitches and its own rhythm. But because they subdivide the same span differently, they interlock polyrhythmically. The ear hears them as **two voices in conversation**, each moving at its own pace.

---


### Tuplets nested in polyrhythm: quintuplets over triplets

Let's go deep: layer **quintuplets** (five notes in the time of four beats) over **triplets** (three notes per beat, so twelve notes in four beats). The two layers subdivide time in completely different ways — five-fold vs. three-fold — creating a dense, tangled polyrhythmic texture.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 88)

(define (quintuplet-line)
  ;; Five notes across four beats
  (let ((span 4.0))
    (for-each
     (lambda (i)
       (note/strike 62 0.2 0.4) ;; D
       (wait (/ span 5)))
     '(0 1 2 3 4))))

(define (triplet-line)
  ;; Three notes per beat, four beats = 12 notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (note/strike 69 0.2 0.5) ;; A
     (wait (/ 1.0 3)))
   (make-list 12 #t)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (quintuplet-line)
  (triplet-line))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, spanning four beats. Top staff: five notes with a \"5\" tuplet bracket (quintuplets across four beats). Bottom staff: twelve notes in triplet eighth-notes (three per beat, four beats). The two layers create a 5-against-12 polyrhythmic texture — only the first and last attacks align; all middle attacks are offset. The quintuplet note-sprites bop at a five-fold rate; the triplet note-sprites at a faster twelve-fold rate. The texture is dense and intricate.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable quintuplet-over-triplet polyrhythm; verify quintuplet attacks at t=0, 0.8, 1.6, 2.4, 3.2 and triplet attacks at t=0, 1/3, 2/3, 1, 4/3, ..., 11/3 -->

This is **advanced polyrhythm** — the kind of texture you hear in contemporary classical music, Balkan folk traditions, and progressive jazz. The two layers don't align except at the boundaries, and the ear hears them as a continuous, rolling **grain** that never settles into a simple pattern.

Quintuplets and twelve-fold triplets *[needs: GAP-1]* — both depend on tuplet support that isn't fully in the engine yet. Once GAP-1 closes, you'll write `(tuplet 5 'eighth)` and `(tuplet 3 'eighth)` and the math will be handled for you.

