### A polyrhythmic ostinato: a repeating cell in 7/8 over 4/4

An **ostinato** is a repeating rhythmic or melodic pattern. When you layer an ostinato in one meter (say, 7/8 — seven eighth-notes per measure) over a bass line in another meter (4/4 — eight eighth-notes per measure), the ostinato's \"downbeat\" shifts on every repetition, creating a **phasing** polyrhythmic texture.

Let's write a seven-note ostinato (one pitch per eighth-note, total duration = 7 eighths = 3.5 beats) and repeat it four times over a steady 4/4 bass (which lasts 16 beats total). The ostinato will phase through the 4/4 grid.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 104)

(define ostinato-pitches '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71)) ;; C D E F G A B (7 notes)

(define (ostinato-7)
  ;; Seven notes, each an eighth-note (0.5 beats), total = 3.5 beats
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.2 0.5)
     (wait 0.5))
   ostinato-pitches))

(define (ostinato-repeated)
  ;; Repeat the ostinato four times (4 * 3.5 = 14 beats)
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (ostinato-7))
   '(0 1 2 3)))

(define (bass-4-4)
  ;; Steady bass on beats 1, 3 for four measures (16 beats total)
  (for-each
   (lambda (i)
     (sfx 'kick)
     (wait 2.0))
   (make-list 8 #t)))

(base/at-beat 0
  (ostinato-repeated)
  (bass-4-4))
```

[VISUAL: Two-staff score, four measures of 4/4. Top staff: a seven-note ostinato (C-D-E-F-G-A-B) repeating four times, each repetition lasting 3.5 beats (7 eighth-notes). The ostinato's \"downbeat\" (the first note, C) falls on beat 0, then beat 3.5, then beat 7, then beat 10.5, phasing through the 4/4 grid. Bottom staff: kick on beats 1, 3 (every other beat, steady 4/4 anchor). The ostinato and bass align on some beats and diverge on others, creating a phasing polyrhythmic texture. The ostinato note-sprites bop at eighth-note rate; the bass at half-note rate.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable 7/8 ostinato over 4/4 bass; verify ostinato repeats starting at t=0, 3.5, 7, 10.5 and bass hits t=0,2,4,6,8,10,12,14 -->

The ostinato **phases** through the 4/4 grid — it starts aligned with the downbeat, then shifts by half a beat on each repetition. After four repetitions, it's shifted by 14 beats total (3.5 * 4 = 14), which is not a multiple of 4, so the pattern never fully re-aligns with the 4/4 measure structure. This is **metric phasing** — a polyrhythmic technique where a repeating pattern drifts through a different metric framework.

---


### Polyrhythm as orchestration: different sections in different meters

You can use polyrhythm to **orchestrate** an ensemble — assign different sections to different meters, so each section subdivides time in its own way.

Let's write a short ensemble piece where:

- **Strings** play a melody in 4/4 (steady quarter-notes).
- **Woodwinds** play a counter-melody in 6/8 (triplet feel, six notes per four beats).
- **Brass** play a bass line in 3/4 (three notes per four beats, creating a hemiola feel).

All three sections sound together, each in its own meter, creating a **polymetric texture**.

```scheme
(transport/tempo 92)

(define (strings-4-4)
  ;; Melody in 4/4: four quarter-notes
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.5 0.6)
     (wait 1.0))
   '(60 62 64 65))) ;; C D E F

(define (woodwinds-6-8)
  ;; Counter-melody in 6/8: six notes in four beats
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.3 0.5)
     (wait (/ 4.0 6)))
   '(67 69 71 72 71 69))) ;; G A B C B A

(define (brass-3-4)
  ;; Bass line in 3/4: three notes in four beats
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.6 0.7)
     (wait (/ 4.0 3)))
   '(48 52 55))) ;; low C E G

(base/at-beat 0
  (strings-4-4)
  (woodwinds-6-8)
  (brass-3-4))
```

[VISUAL: Three-staff score, spanning four beats. Top staff (strings, treble clef): melody C-D-E-F in quarter-notes (4/4). Middle staff (woodwinds, treble clef): counter-melody G-A-B-C-B-A in six equal divisions (6/8 feel). Bottom staff (brass, bass clef): bass line low C-E-G in three equal divisions (3/4 feel, hemiola). The three sections interlock, creating a polymetric texture where each voice moves in its own metric world. The note-sprites on each staff bop at different rates (quarter-note, triplet, hemiola), visually reinforcing the polyrhythmic/polymetric structure.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable polymetric ensemble with strings in 4/4, woodwinds in 6/8, brass in 3/4; verify strings at t=0,1,2,3, woodwinds at t=0,2/3,4/3,2,8/3,10/3, brass at t=0,4/3,8/3 -->

This is **polymeter** — a special case of polyrhythm where each voice is in a different **time signature**, but all voices sound together in the same span of clock time. The ear hears three independent metric worlds coexisting.

---


### A polyrhythmic round: canon with phase-shifted entries

A **round** (Ch9) is a canon where each voice enters at a different time but sings the same melody. A **polyrhythmic round** adds a twist: each voice sings the melody in a different **subdivision**, so the voices interlock polyrhythmically as well as canonically.

Let's write a three-voice round where:

- **Voice 1** sings a four-note melody in quarter-notes (one note per beat).
- **Voice 2** sings the same melody in triplet eighths (three notes per two beats, so the melody lasts 8/3 beats).
- **Voice 3** sings the same melody in dotted eighths (each note 0.75 beats, so the melody lasts 3 beats).

All three voices sing the same pitches, but at different rates, and they enter at different times (staggered by one beat).

```scheme
(transport/tempo 96)

(define melody '(60 64 67 72)) ;; C E G high C

(define (voice-1)
  ;; Quarter-notes (one beat per note)
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.4 0.6)
     (wait 1.0))
   melody))

(define (voice-2)
  ;; Triplet subdivision: each note 2/3 beat
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.3 0.5)
     (wait (/ 2.0 3)))
   melody))

(define (voice-3)
  ;; Dotted eighth subdivision: each note 0.75 beat
  (for-each
   (lambda (pitch)
     (note/strike pitch 0.35 0.55)
     (wait 0.75))
   melody))

;; Stagger entries: voice 1 at beat 0, voice 2 at beat 1, voice 3 at beat 2
(base/at-beat 0 (voice-1))
(base/at-beat 1 (voice-2))
(base/at-beat 2 (voice-3))
```

[VISUAL: Three-staff score, spanning about six beats. Top staff (voice 1): melody C-E-G-C in quarter-notes, starting at beat 0. Middle staff (voice 2): the same melody in triplet eighths (each note 2/3 beat), starting at beat 1. Bottom staff (voice 3): the same melody in dotted eighths (each note 0.75 beat), starting at beat 2. The three voices cascade, each singing the same tune but at a different rate and starting at a different time. The note-sprites on each staff bop at their own subdivision rate, creating a visual polyrhythmic cascade.]

<!-- BUILD: runnable polyrhythmic round with three voices in quarter-notes, triplets, and dotted eighths, entries staggered by one beat; verify voice 1 at t=0,1,2,3, voice 2 at t=1, 1+2/3, 1+4/3, 1+2, voice 3 at t=2, 2.75, 3.5, 4.25 -->

This is a **canon in both pitch and rhythm** — the melody is the same, but each voice unfolds it in a different metric subdivision. The result is a **cascading polyrhythmic texture** where the same tune weaves through itself at three different rates.

---

